# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brownout-electricity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] An **induction motor** or **asynchronous motor** is an AC electric motor in which the electric current in the rotor that produces torque is obtained by electromagnetic induction from the magnetic field of the stator winding.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] An induction motor therefore needs no electrical connections to the rotor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] An induction motor's rotor can be either wound type or squirrel-cage type.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Three-phase squirrel-cage induction motors are widely used as industrial drives because they are self-starting, reliable, and economical.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Single-phase induction motors are used extensively for smaller loads, such as garbage disposals and stationary power tools.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Although traditionally used for constant-speed service, single- and three-phase induction motors are increasingly being installed in variable-speed applications using variable-frequency drives (VFD).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] VFD offers energy savings opportunities for induction motors in applications like fans, pumps, and compressors that have a variable load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In 1824, the French physicist François Arago formulated the existence of rotating magnetic fields, termed Arago's rotations.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] By manually turning switches on and off, Walter Baily demonstrated this in 1879, effectively the first primitive induction motor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The first commutator-free single-phase AC induction motor was invented by Hungarian engineer Ottó Bláthy; he used the single-phase motor to propel his invention, the electricity meter.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The first AC commutator-free polyphase induction motors were independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla, a working motor model having been demonstrated by the former in 1885 and by the latter in 1887.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Tesla applied for US patents in October and November 1887 and was granted some of these patents in May 1888.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In April 1888, the *Royal Academy of Science of Turin* published Ferraris's research on his AC polyphase motor detailing the foundations of motor operation.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] George Westinghouse, who was developing an alternating current power system at that time, licensed Tesla's patents in 1888 and purchased a US patent option on Ferraris' induction motor concept.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Tesla was also employed for one year as a consultant.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Scott was assigned to assist Tesla and later took over development of the induction motor at Westinghouse.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Steadfast in his promotion of three-phase development, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky invented the cage-rotor induction motor in 1889 and the three-limb transformer in 1890.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Furthermore, he claimed that Tesla's motor was not practical because of two-phase pulsations, which prompted him to persist in his three-phase work.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Although Westinghouse achieved its first practical induction motor in 1892 and developed a line of polyphase 60 hertz induction motors in 1893, these early Westinghouse motors were two-phase motors with wound rotors until B.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Lamme developed a rotating bar winding rotor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The General Electric Company (GE) began developing three-phase induction motors in 1891.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] By 1896, General Electric and Westinghouse signed a cross-licensing agreement for the bar-winding-rotor design, later called the squirrel-cage rotor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Kennelly was the first to bring out the full significance of complex numbers (using *j* to represent the square root of minus one) to designate the 90º rotation operator in analysis of AC problems.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] GE's Charles Proteus Steinmetz improved the application of AC complex quantities and developed an analytical model called the induction motor Steinmetz equivalent circuit.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Induction motor improvements flowing from these inventions and innovations were such that a 100-horsepower induction motor built in the 1970s had the same mounting dimensions as a 7.5-horsepower motor in 1897.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In both induction and synchronous motors, the AC power supplied to the motor's stator creates a magnetic field that rotates in synchronism with the AC oscillations.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Whereas a synchronous motor's rotor turns at the same rate as the stator field, an induction motor's rotor rotates at a somewhat slower speed than the stator field.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The induction motor's stator magnetic field is therefore changing or rotating relative to the rotor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] This induces an opposing current in the rotor, in effect the motor's secondary winding.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The rotating magnetic flux induces currents in the rotor windings, in a manner similar to currents induced in a transformer's secondary winding(s).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The induced currents in the rotor windings in turn create magnetic fields in the rotor that react against the stator field.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The direction of the rotor magnetic field opposes the change in current through the rotor windings, following Lenz's Law.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The cause of induced current in the rotor windings is the rotating stator magnetic field, so to oppose the change in rotor-winding currents the rotor turns in the direction of the stator magnetic field.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The rotor accelerates until the magnitude of induced rotor current and torque balances the load on the rotor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Since rotation at synchronous speed does not induce rotor current, an induction motor always operates slightly slower than synchronous speed.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The difference, or "slip," between actual and synchronous speed varies from about 0.5% to 5.0% for standard Design B torque curve induction motors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The induction motor's essential character is that torque is created solely by induction instead of the rotor being separately excited as in synchronous or DC machines or being self-magnetized as in permanent magnet motors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] For rotor currents to be induced, the speed of the physical rotor must be either slower or faster than that of the stator's rotating magnetic field ( $n_{s}$ ); otherwise the magnetic field would not be moving relative to the rotor conductors and no currents would be induced.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] As the speed of the rotor drops below synchronous speed, the rotation rate of the magnetic field in the rotor increases, inducing more current in the windings and creating more torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The ratio between the rotation rate of the magnetic field induced in the rotor and the rotation rate of the stator's rotating field is called "slip".
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Under load, the speed drops and the slip increases enough to create sufficient torque to turn the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] For this reason, induction motors are sometimes referred to as "asynchronous motors".
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] An induction motor can be used as an induction generator, or it can be unrolled to form a linear induction motor which can directly generate linear motion.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The generating mode for induction motors is complicated by the need to excite the rotor, which begins with only residual magnetization.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In some cases, that residual magnetization is enough to self-excite the motor under load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Therefore, it is necessary to either snap the motor and connect it momentarily to a live grid or to add capacitors charged initially by residual magnetism and providing the required reactive power during operation.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Similar is the operation of the induction motor in parallel with a synchronous motor serving as a power factor compensator.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] A feature in the generator mode in parallel to the grid is that the rotor speed is higher than in the driving mode.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Then active energy is being given to the grid.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Another disadvantage of the induction motor generator is that it consumes a significant magnetizing current **I**0 = (20–35)%.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] An AC motor's synchronous speed, $f_{s}$ , is the rotation rate of the stator's magnetic field $f_{s}={2f \over p},$ where f is the frequency of the power supply in hertz and p is the number of magnetic poles.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The number of magnetic poles, p , is the number of north and south poles per phase.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] For example; a single-phase motor with 3 north and 3 south poles, having 6 poles per phase, is a 6-pole motor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] A three-phase motor with 18 north and 18 south poles, having 6 poles per phase, is also a 6-pole motor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] This industry standard method of counting poles results in the same synchronous speed for a given frequency regardless of polarity.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Slip, s , is defined as the difference between synchronous speed and operating speed, at the same frequency, expressed in rpm, or in percentage or ratio of synchronous speed.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] where $n_{s}$ is stator electrical speed, $n_{r}$ is rotor electrical speed.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The equation is correct for small and moderate amounts of slip, but not for large amounts of slip, such as a stopped rotor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Double revolving field theory in the next section, provides a better approximation to actual torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Slip, which varies from zero at synchronous speed and 1 when the rotor is stalled, influences the motor's torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Because the short-circuited rotor windings have small resistance, even a small slip induces a large current in the rotor and produces significant torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] At full rated load, slip varies from more than 5% for small or special purpose motors to less than 1% for large motors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] These speed variations can cause load-sharing problems when differently sized motors are mechanically connected.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Various methods are available to reduce slip, VFDs often offering the best solution.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The rotor of an induction motor is subject to two rotating magnet fields, which rotate in opposite directions.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Torque is the result of the difference between these two rotating fields.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The illustration shows torque as a function of slip.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The green line shows torque developed by a single-phase induction motor, without a starting winding.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] No torque is developed when the rotor is stopped.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] A slight push in either direction will cause the rotor to accelerate in the direction that it was pushed.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Torque is on the vertical axis shown as a green line, and slip is on the horizontal axis.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Slip ranges from zero to zero, corresponding to the reverse and forward directions of the rotor, with 1.0 slip in the center as the point where the rotor is stopped and no torque is produced.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Torque is the net result of two counter-rotating magnetic fields, with one shown as a blue line, and the other shown as a red line.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The red and blue lines are mirror images of the typical torque curve shown in the previous section.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The typical speed-torque relationship of a standard NEMA Design B polyphase induction motor is as shown in the curve at right.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Over a motor's normal load range, the torque's slope is approximately linear or proportional to slip because the value of rotor resistance divided by slip, $R_{r}'/s$ , dominates torque in a linear manner.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] As load increases above rated load, stator and rotor leakage reactance factors gradually become more significant in relation to $R_{r}'/s$ such that torque gradually curves towards breakdown torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] As the load torque increases beyond breakdown torque the motor stalls.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] There are three basic types of small induction motors: split-phase single-phase, shaded-pole single-phase, and polyphase.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In two-pole single-phase motors, the torque goes to zero at 100% slip (zero speed), so these require alterations to the stator such as shaded-poles to provide starting torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] A single phase induction motor requires separate starting circuitry to provide a rotating field to the motor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The normal running windings within such a single-phase motor can cause the rotor to turn in either direction, so the starting circuit determines the operating direction.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In certain smaller single-phase motors, starting is done by means of a copper wire turn around part of a pole; such a pole is referred to as a shaded pole.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The current induced in this turn lags behind the supply current, creating a delayed magnetic field around the shaded part of the pole face.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] This imparts sufficient rotational field energy to start the motor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] These motors are typically used in applications such as desk fans and record players, as the required starting torque is low, and the low efficiency is tolerable relative to the reduced cost of the motor and starting method compared to other AC motor designs.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Larger single phase motors are split-phase motors and have a second stator winding fed with out-of-phase current; such currents may be created by feeding the winding through a capacitor or having it receive different values of inductance and resistance from the main winding.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The *capacitor-run* designs keep the second winding on when running, improving torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] A *resistance start* design uses a starter inserted in series with the startup winding, creating reactance.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Self-starting polyphase induction motors produce torque even at standstill.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Available squirrel-cage induction motor starting methods include direct-on-line starting, reduced-voltage reactor or auto-transformer starting, star-delta starting or, increasingly, new solid-state soft assemblies and, of course, variable frequency drives (VFDs).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Polyphase motors have rotor bars shaped to give different speed-torque characteristics.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The current distribution within the rotor bars varies depending on the frequency of the induced current.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] At standstill, the rotor current is the same frequency as the stator current, and tends to travel at the outermost parts of the cage rotor bars (by skin effect).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The different bar shapes can give usefully different speed-torque characteristics as well as some control over the inrush current at startup.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Although polyphase motors are inherently self-starting, their starting and pull-up torque design limits must be high enough to overcome actual load conditions.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In wound rotor motors, rotor circuit connection through slip rings to external resistances allows change of speed-torque characteristics for acceleration control and speed control purposes.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Before the development of semiconductor power electronics, it was difficult to vary the frequency, and cage induction motors were mainly used in fixed speed applications.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Applications, such as electric overhead cranes, used DC drives or wound rotor motors (WRIM) with slip rings for rotor circuit connection to variable external resistance allowing considerable range of speed control.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] However, resistor losses associated with low speed operation of WRIMs is a major cost disadvantage, especially for constant loads.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Large slip ring motor drives, termed slip energy recovery systems, some still in use, recover energy from the rotor circuit, rectify it, and return it to the power system using a VFD.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The speed of a pair of slip-ring motors can be controlled by a cascade connection, or concatenation.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The rotor of one motor is connected to the stator of the other.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] If the two motors are also mechanically connected, they will run at half speed.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] This system was once widely used in three-phase AC railway locomotives, such as FS Class E.333.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] By the turn of this century, however, such cascade-based electromechanical systems became much more efficiently and economically solved using power semiconductor elements solutions.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In many industrial variable-speed applications, DC and WRIM drives are being displaced by VFD-fed cage induction motors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The most common efficient way to control asynchronous motor speed of many loads is with VFDs.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Barriers to adoption of VFDs due to cost and reliability considerations have been reduced considerably over the past three decades such that it is estimated that drive technology is adopted in as many as 30–40% of all newly installed motors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Variable frequency drives implement the scalar or vector control of an induction motor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] With scalar control, only the magnitude and frequency of the supply voltage are controlled without phase control (absent feedback by rotor position).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Scalar control is suitable for application where the load is constant.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Vector control allows independent control of the speed and torque of the motor, making it possible to maintain a constant rotation speed at varying load torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] But vector control is more expensive because of the cost of the sensor (not always) and the requirement for a more powerful controller.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The stator of an induction motor consists of poles carrying supply current to induce a magnetic field that penetrates the rotor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] To optimize the distribution of the magnetic field, windings are distributed in slots around the stator, with the magnetic field having the same number of north and south poles.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Induction motors are most commonly run on single-phase or three-phase power, but two-phase motors exist; in theory, induction motors can have any number of phases.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Many single-phase motors having two windings can be viewed as two-phase motors, since a capacitor is used to generate a second power phase 90° from the single-phase supply and feeds it to the second motor winding.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Single-phase motors require some mechanism to produce a rotating field on startup.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Induction motors using a squirrel-cage rotor winding may have the rotor bars skewed slightly to smooth out torque in each revolution.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Standardized NEMA & IEC motor frame sizes throughout the industry result in interchangeable dimensions for shaft, foot mounting, general aspects as well as certain motor flange aspect.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Since an open drip proof (ODP) motor design allows a free air exchange from outside to the inner stator windings, this style of motor tends to be slightly more efficient because the windings are cooler.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] At a given power rating, lower speed requires a larger frame.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The method of changing the direction of rotation of an induction motor depends on whether it is a three-phase or single-phase machine.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] A three-phase motor can be reversed by swapping any two of its phase connections.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Motors required to change direction regularly (such as hoists) will have extra switching contacts in their controller to reverse rotation as needed.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] A variable frequency drive nearly always permits reversal by electronically changing the phase sequence of voltage applied to the motor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] In a single-phase split-phase motor, reversal is achieved by reversing the connections of the starting winding.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Some motors bring out the start winding connections to allow selection of rotation direction at installation.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] If the start winding is permanently connected within the motor, it is impractical to reverse the sense of rotation.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Single-phase shaded-pole motors have a fixed rotation unless a second set of shading windings is provided.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The power factor of induction motors varies with load, typically from about 0.85 or 0.90 at full load to as low as about 0.20 at no-load, due to stator and rotor leakage and magnetizing reactances.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Power factor can be improved by connecting capacitors either on an individual motor basis or, by preference, on a common bus covering several motors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] For economic and other considerations, power systems are rarely power factor corrected to unity power factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Power capacitor application with harmonic currents requires power system analysis to avoid harmonic resonance between capacitors and transformer and circuit reactances.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Common bus power factor correction is recommended to minimize resonant risk and to simplify power system analysis.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Regulatory authorities in many countries have implemented legislation to encourage the manufacture and use of higher efficiency electric motors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Some legislation mandates the future use of premium-efficiency induction motors in certain equipment.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The equivalent circuit is a single-phase representation of a multiphase induction motor that is valid in steady-state balanced-load conditions.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Paraphrasing from Alger in Knowlton, an induction motor is simply an electrical transformer the magnetic circuit of which is separated by an air gap between the stator winding and the moving rotor winding.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] The equivalent circuit can accordingly be shown either with equivalent circuit components of respective windings separated by an ideal transformer or with rotor components referred to the stator side as shown in the following circuit and associated equation and parameter definition tables.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Linear induction motors, which work on the same general principles as rotary induction motors (frequently three-phase), are designed to produce straight line motion.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-induction-motor] Uses include magnetic levitation, linear propulsion, linear actuators, and liquid metal pumping.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In an electric circuit, instantaneous power is the time rate of flow of energy past a given point of the circuit.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In alternating current circuits, energy storage elements such as inductors and capacitors may result in periodic reversals of the direction of energy flow.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The portion of instantaneous power that, averaged over a complete cycle of the AC waveform, results in net transfer of energy in one direction is known as instantaneous active power, and its time average is known as **active power** or **real power**.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The portion of instantaneous power that results in no net transfer of energy but instead oscillates between the source and load in each cycle due to stored energy is known as instantaneous reactive power, and its amplitude is the absolute value of **reactive power**.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The **instantaneous power** is given by the product: $p(t)=v(t)i(t)=2{|V|}{|I|}\cos(\omega t)\cos(\omega t-\varphi ).$ If the load is purely resistive, the two quantities reverse their polarity at the same time.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Hence, the instantaneous power is always positive, such that the direction of energy flow does not reverse and always is toward the resistor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In this case, only active power is transferred.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] If the load is purely *reactive*, then the voltage and current are 90 degrees out of phase.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] For two quarters of each cycle, the product of voltage and current is positive, but for the other two quarters, the product is negative, indicating that on average, exactly as much energy flows into the load as flows back out.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] There is no net energy flow over each half cycle.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In this case, only reactive power flows: There is no net transfer of energy to the load; however, electrical power does flow along the wires and returns by flowing in reverse along the same wires.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The current required for this reactive power flow dissipates energy in the line resistance, even if the ideal load device consumes no energy itself.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Practical loads have resistance as well as inductance, or capacitance, so both active and reactive powers will flow to normal loads.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Apparent power is the product of the RMS values of voltage and current.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Apparent power is taken into account when designing and operating power systems, because although the current associated with reactive power does no work at the load, it still must be supplied by the power source.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Conductors, transformers and generators must be sized to carry the total current, not just the current that does useful work.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Insufficient reactive power can depress voltage levels on an electrical grid and, under certain operating conditions, collapse the network (a blackout).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Another consequence is that adding the apparent power for two loads will not accurately give the total power unless they have the same phase difference between current and voltage (the same power factor).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Conventionally, capacitors are treated as if they generate reactive power, and inductors are treated as if they consume it.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] If a capacitor and an inductor are placed in parallel, then the currents flowing through the capacitor and the inductor tend to cancel rather than add.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This is the fundamental mechanism for controlling the power factor in electric power transmission; capacitors (or inductors) are inserted in a circuit to partially compensate for reactive power 'consumed' ('generated') by the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Purely capacitive circuits supply reactive power with the current waveform leading the voltage waveform by 90 degrees, while purely inductive circuits absorb reactive power with the current waveform lagging the voltage waveform by 90 degrees.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The result of this is that capacitive and inductive circuit elements tend to cancel each other out.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] These are all denoted in the adjacent diagram (called a power triangle).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In the diagram, *P* is the active power, *Q* is the reactive power (in this case positive), *S* is the complex power and the length of *S* is the apparent power.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Reactive power does not do any work, so it is represented as the **imaginary axis** of the vector diagram.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Active power does do work, so it is the real axis.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The unit for power is the watt (symbol: W).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Apparent power is often expressed in volt-amperes (VA) since it is the product of RMS voltage and RMS current.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The unit for reactive power is var, which stands for volt-ampere reactive.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Since reactive power transfers no net energy to the load, it is sometimes called "wattless" power.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] It does, however, serve an important function in electrical grids and its lack has been cited as a significant factor in the Northeast blackout of 2003.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Understanding the relationship among these three quantities lies at the heart of understanding power engineering.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The mathematical relationship among them can be represented by vectors or expressed using complex numbers, *S* = *P* + *j Q* (where *j* is the imaginary unit).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] where V and I are the complex valued voltage and current, respectively, written in phasor form with the amplitude as RMS.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Also by convention, the complex conjugate of *I* is used, which is denoted $I^{*}$ (or ${\overline {I}}$ ), rather than *I* itself.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This is done because otherwise using the product V I to define S would result in a quantity that depends on the reference angle chosen for V or I, but defining S as V I* results in a quantity that doesn't depend on the reference angle and allows to relate S to P and Q.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Other forms of complex power (units in volt-amps, VA) are derived from *Z*, the load impedance (units in ohms, Ω).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] where *X* denotes reactance (units in ohms, Ω) of the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] These are simplified diagrammatically by the power triangle.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The ratio of active power to apparent power in a circuit is called the power factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] For two systems transmitting the same amount of active power, the system with the lower power factor will have higher circulating currents due to energy that returns to the source from energy storage in the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] These higher currents produce higher losses and reduce overall transmission efficiency.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] A lower power factor circuit will have a higher apparent power and higher losses for the same amount of active power.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The power factor is 1.0 when the voltage and current are in phase.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] It is zero when the current leads or lags the voltage by 90 degrees.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] When the voltage and current are 180 degrees out of phase, the power factor is negative one, and the load is feeding energy into the source (an example would be a home with solar cells on the roof that feed power into the power grid when the sun is shining).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Power factors are usually stated as "leading" or "lagging" to show the sign of the phase angle of current with respect to voltage.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Voltage is designated as the base to which current angle is compared, meaning that current is thought of as either "leading" or "lagging" voltage.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Where the waveforms are purely sinusoidal, the power factor is the cosine of the phase angle ( $\varphi$ ) between the current and voltage sinusoidal waveforms.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Equipment data sheets and nameplates will often abbreviate power factor as " $\cos \varphi$ " for this reason.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Example: The active power is 700 W and the phase angle between voltage and current is 45.6°.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In a direct current circuit, the power flowing to the load is proportional to the product of the current through the load and the potential drop across the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The power that happens because of a capacitor or inductor is called reactive power.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] It happens because of the AC nature of elements like inductors and capacitors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Energy flows in one direction from the source to the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In AC power, the voltage and current both vary approximately sinusoidally.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] When there is inductance or capacitance in the circuit, the voltage and current waveforms do not line up perfectly.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The power flow has two components – one component flows from source to load and can perform work at the load; the other portion, known as "reactive power", is due to the delay between voltage and current, known as phase angle, and cannot do useful work at the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] It can be thought of as current that is arriving at the wrong time (too late or too early).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] To distinguish reactive power from active power, it is measured in units of "volt-amperes reactive", or var.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] These units can simplify to watts but are left as var to denote that they represent no actual work output.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Energy stored in capacitive or inductive elements of the network gives rise to reactive power flow.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Reactive power flow strongly influences the voltage levels across the network.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Voltage levels and reactive power flow must be carefully controlled to allow a power system to be operated within acceptable limits.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] A technique known as reactive compensation is used to reduce apparent power flow to a load by reducing reactive power supplied from transmission lines and providing it locally.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] For example, to compensate an inductive load, a shunt capacitor is installed close to the load itself.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This allows all reactive power needed by the load to be supplied by the capacitor and not have to be transferred over the transmission lines.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This practice saves energy because it reduces the amount of energy that is required to be produced by the utility to do the same amount of work.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Additionally, it allows for more efficient transmission line designs using smaller conductors or fewer bundled conductors and optimizing the design of transmission towers.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Stored energy in the magnetic or electric field of a load device, such as a motor or capacitor, causes an offset between the current and the voltage waveforms.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] A capacitor is a device that stores energy in the form of an electric field.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] As current is driven through the capacitor, charge build-up causes an opposing voltage to develop across the capacitor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This voltage increases until some maximum dictated by the capacitor structure.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In an AC network, the voltage across a capacitor is constantly changing.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The capacitor opposes this change, causing the current to lead the voltage in phase.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Capacitors are said to "source" reactive power, and thus to cause a leading power factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Induction machines are some of the most common types of loads in the electric power system today.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] These machines use inductors, or large coils of wire to store energy in the form of a magnetic field.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] When a voltage is initially placed across the coil, the inductor strongly resists this change in a current and magnetic field, which causes a time delay for the current to reach its maximum value.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This causes the current to lag behind the voltage in phase.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Inductors are said to "sink" reactive power, and thus to cause a lagging power factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Induction generators can source or sink reactive power, and provide a measure of control to system operators over reactive power flow and thus voltage.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Because these devices have opposite effects on the phase angle between voltage and current, they can be used to "cancel out" each other's effects.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This usually takes the form of capacitor banks being used to counteract the lagging power factor caused by induction motors.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Transmission connected generators are generally required to support reactive power flow.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] For example, on the United Kingdom transmission system, generators are required by the Grid Code Requirements to supply their rated power between the limits of 0.85 power factor lagging and 0.90 power factor leading at the designated terminals.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The "system gain" is an important source of reactive power in the above power balance equation, which is generated by the capacitative nature of the transmission network itself.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] By making decisive switching actions in the early morning before the demand increases, the system gain can be maximized early on, helping to secure the system for the whole day.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] To balance the equation some pre-fault reactive generator use will be required.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Other sources of reactive power that will also be used include shunt capacitors, shunt reactors, static VAR compensators and voltage control circuits.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] While active power and reactive power are well defined in any system, the definition of apparent power for unbalanced polyphase systems is considered to be one of the most controversial topics in power engineering.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Originally, apparent power arose merely as a figure of merit.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Major delineations of the concept are attributed to Stanley's *Phenomena of Retardation in the Induction Coil* (1888) and Steinmetz's *Theoretical Elements of Engineering* (1915).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] However, with the development of three-phase power distribution, it became clear that the definition of apparent power and the power factor could not be applied to unbalanced polyphase systems.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In 1920, a "Special Joint Committee of the AIEE and the National Electric Light Association" met to resolve the issue.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] that is, the magnitude of total three-phase complex power.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The 1920 committee found no consensus and the topic continued to dominate discussions.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In 1932, another committee formed and once again failed to resolve the question.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] The transcripts of their discussions are the lengthiest and most controversial ever published by the AIEE.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Further resolution of this debate did not come until the late 1990s.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] $V^{+}$ denotes the positive sequence voltage phasor, and $I^{+}$ denotes the positive sequence current phasor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] A perfect resistor stores no energy; so current and voltage are in phase.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Therefore, there is no reactive power and $P=S$ (using the passive sign convention).
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] For a perfect capacitor or inductor, there is no net power transfer; so all power is reactive.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] where *X* is the reactance of the capacitor or inductor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] where $v(t)$ and $i(t)$ are the time-varying voltage and current waveforms.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This definition is useful because it applies to all waveforms, whether they are sinusoidal or not.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This is particularly useful in power electronics, where non-sinusoidal waveforms are common.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In general, engineers are interested in the active power averaged over a period of time, whether it is a low frequency line cycle or a high frequency power converter switching period.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] This method of calculating the average power gives the active power regardless of harmonic content of the waveform.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Since an RMS value can be calculated for any waveform, apparent power can be calculated from this.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] For active power it would at first appear that it would be necessary to calculate many product terms and average all of them.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] However, looking at one of these product terms in more detail produces a very interesting result.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] However, the time average of a function of the form cos(*ωt* + *k*) is zero provided that *ω* is nonzero.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Therefore, the only product terms that have a nonzero average are those where the frequency of voltage and current match.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] In other words, it is possible to calculate active (average) power by simply treating each frequency separately and adding up the answers.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Furthermore, if voltage of the mains supply is assumed to be a single frequency (which it usually is), this shows that harmonic currents are a bad thing.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] They will increase the RMS current (since there will be non-zero terms added) and therefore apparent power, but they will have no effect on the active power transferred.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Hence, harmonic currents will reduce the power factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Harmonic currents can be reduced by a filter placed at the input of the device.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] Typically this will consist of either just a capacitor (relying on parasitic resistance and inductance in the supply) or a capacitor-inductor network.
[src:brownout-electricity/ac-power] An active power factor correction circuit at the input would generally reduce the harmonic currents further and maintain the power factor closer to unity.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] "Ancillary services are all services required by the transmission or distribution system operator to enable them to maintain the integrity and stability of the transmission or distribution system as well as the power quality".
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Ancillary services are specialty services and functions provided by actors within the electric grid that facilitate and support the continuous flow of electricity, so that the demand for electrical energy is met in real time.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] The term ancillary services is used to refer to a variety of operations beyond generation and transmission that are required to maintain grid stability and security.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] These services generally include active power control or frequency control and reactive power control or voltage control, on various timescales.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Traditionally, ancillary services have been provided by large production units such as synchronous generators.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] With the integration of more intermittent generation and the development of smart grid technologies, the provision of ancillary services is extended to smaller distributed generation and consumption units.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Electricity frequency is directly connected to the balance of consumption and generation of active power ( $\Delta P=P_{generation}-P_{consume}$ ) and the total rotating energy ( $W_{tot,kin}$ ) of the synchronous power system.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Where S is the total exchange of active power for the entire grid and H is the normalized inertia constant for the system.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] A system with a small amount of total rotating kinetic energy will be more sensitive to deviations in $\Delta P$ , as the frequency's derivative will be more significantly affected.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] As the total inertia of synchronous grids decreases due to the increasing integration of renewable generation sources, the methodologies and requirements for enabling converter-based generation units to control grid frequency with greater speed and precision are becoming more important.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Frequency control refers to the need to ensure that the grid frequency stays within a specific range of the nominal frequency.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Mismatch between electricity generation and demand causes variations in frequency, so control services are required to bring the frequency back to its nominal value and ensure it does not vary out of range.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] where Pm is the change in power of the system.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] If we have multiple generators, each might have its own R.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] This simple equation can be rearranged to find the change in power that corresponds to a given change in frequency.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Consumer loads expect voltage within a certain range, and the regulators require it be within a certain percent of the nominal voltage (for example, in the US it is ±5%).
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Reactive power can be used to compensate the voltage drops, but must be provided closer to the loads than real power needs (this is because reactive power tend to travel badly through the grid).
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Notice that voltage can be controlled also using transformer taps and voltage regulators.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Scheduling and dispatch are necessary because in most electrical systems energy storage is nearly zero, so at any instant, the power into the system (produced by a generator) must equal the power out of the system (demand from consumers).
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Since production must so closely match demand, careful scheduling and dispatch are necessary.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Usually performed by the independent system operator or transmission system operator, both are services dedicated to the commitment and coordination of the generation and transmission units in order to maintain the reliability of the power grid.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Scheduling refers to before-the-fact actions (like scheduling a generator to produce a certain amount of power the next week), while dispatch refers to the real-time control of the available resources.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Since production and demand must match so perfectly (see Scheduling and dispatch), operating reserves help make up the difference when production is too low.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] An operating reserve is a generator that can quickly be dispatched to ensure that there is sufficient energy generation to meet load.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Spinning reserves are generators that are already online and can rapidly increase their power output to meet fast changes in demand.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Spinning reserves are required because demand can vary on short timescales and rapid response is needed.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Other operating reserves are generators that can be dispatched by the operator to meet demand, but that cannot respond as quickly as spinning reserves, and grid battery storage that can respond within tens of milliseconds, generally faster than even spinning reserve.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] The grid integration of renewable generation simultaneously requires additional ancillary services and has the potential to provide ancillary services to the grid.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] The inverters that are installed with distributed generation systems and roof top solar systems have the potential to provide many of the ancillary services that are traditionally provided by spinning generators and voltage regulators.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] These services include reactive power compensation, voltage regulation, flicker control, active power filtering and harmonic cancellation.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Wind turbines with variable-speed generators have the potential to add synthetic inertia to the grid and assist in frequency control.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] CAISO tested the 131 MW Tule wind farm's synchronverter in 2018, and found it could perform some of the grid services similar or better than traditional generators.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Hydro-Québec began requiring synthetic inertia in 2005 as the first grid operator, demanding a temporary 6% power boost when countering frequency drop by combining the power electronics with the rotational inertia of a wind turbine rotor.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Similar requirements came into effect in Europe in 2016.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles have the potential to be utilized to provide ancillary services to the grid, specifically load regulation and spinning reserves.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles can behave like distributed energy storage and have the potential to discharge power back to the grid through bidirectional flow, referred to as vehicle-to-grid (V2G).
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles have the ability to supply power at a fast rate which enables them to be used like spinning reserves and provide grid stability with the increased use of intermittent generation such as wind and solar.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] According to the study cited in the reference, which compared the profitability of offering operating reserve ancillary service with the sales of V2G energy from a fleet of vehicles, providing operating reserve regulation service is more profitable than selling V2G energy alone.
[src:brownout-electricity/ancillary-services] However, the technologies to utilize electric vehicles to provide ancillary services are not yet widely implemented, but there is much anticipation of their potential.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An **arc-fault circuit interrupter** (**AFCI**) or **arc-fault detection device** (**AFDD**) is a circuit breaker that breaks the circuit when it detects the electric arcs that are a signature of loose connections in home wiring.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Loose connections, which can develop over time, can sometimes become hot enough to ignite house fires.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An AFCI selectively distinguishes between a harmless arc (incidental to normal operation of switches, plugs, and brushed motors), and a potentially dangerous arc (that can occur, for example, in a lamp cord which has a broken conductor).
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In regions using 230 V, the combination of higher voltage and lower load currents lead to different conditions being required to initiate an arc fault that does not either burn clear or weld to a short circuit after a short time, and there are different arc characteristics once struck.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Because of this, in Western Europe (where in many countries a domestic supply may be 400V 3 phase) and the UK (where domestically a single phase 230V supply is common), adoption is slower, and their use is optional, only being mandated in specified high risk locations.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The Australian and New Zealand regulations – Wiring Rules (AS NZS 3000:2018) do not require installation of AFDDs in Australia.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] However, in New Zealand all final sub-circuits with ratings up to 20 A will require protection by an AFDD if they supply locations with significant fire risk, locations containing irreplaceable items, certain historic buildings, and socket-outlets in school sleeping accommodation.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Most sockets in these countries are on circuits rated at 20 A or less.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In the US, arc faults are said to be one of the leading causes for residential electrical fires.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Each year in the United States, over 40,000 fires are attributed to home electrical wiring.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] These fires result in over 350 deaths and over 1,400 injuries each year.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Conventional circuit breakers respond only to overloads and short circuits, so they do not protect against arcing conditions that produce erratic, and often reduced current.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs are devices designed to protect against fires caused by arcing faults in the home electrical wiring.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI circuitry continuously monitors the current and discriminates between normal and unwanted arcing conditions.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Once detected, the AFCI opens its internal contacts, thus de-energizing the circuit and reducing the potential for a fire to occur.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The electronics inside an AFCI breaker detect electrical current alternating at characteristic frequencies, usually around 100 kHz, known to be associated with wire arcing, which are sustained for more than a few milliseconds.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A *combination AFCI breaker* provides protection against parallel arcing (line to neutral), series arcing (a loose, broken, or otherwise high resistance segment in a single line), ground arcing (from line or neutral to ground), overload, and short circuit.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI will open the circuit if dangerous arcing is detected.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] When installed as the first outlet on a branch circuit, AFCI receptacles provide series arc protection for the entire branch circuit.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] They also provide parallel arc protection for the branch circuit starting at the AFCI receptacle.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Unlike AFCI breakers, AFCI receptacles may be used on any wiring system regardless of the panel.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Starting with the 1999 version of the *National Electrical Code* in the United States, and the 2002 version of the *Canadian Electrical Code* in Canada, the national codes require AFCIs in all circuits that feed outlets in bedrooms of dwelling units.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] They are also required in dormitory units.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Not all U.S. jurisdictions have adopted the NEC's AFCI requirements so it is important to check local code requirements.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI is intended to prevent fire from arcs.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI circuit breakers are designed to meet one of two standards as specified by UL 1699: "branch" type or "combination" type (note: the Canadian Electrical Code uses different terminology but similar technical requirements).
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A branch type AFCI trips on 75 amperes of arcing current from the line wire to either the neutral or ground wire.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A combination type adds series arcing detection to branch type performance.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Combination type AFCIs trip on 5 amperes of series arcing.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI receptacles are an alternative solution to AFCI breakers.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] These receptacles are designed to address the dangers associated with both types of potentially hazardous arcing: parallel and series.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI receptacles offer the benefit of localized *test* and *reset* with such buttons located on the face of the device.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This can save a journey to the breaker panel but can also encourage simply resetting by a user without investigating the underlying fault, as would presumably happen if someone with access to the electrical panel was notified.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In 2002, the NEC removed the word "receptacle", leaving "outlets", with the effect that lights and other wired-in devices such as ceiling fans within bedrooms were added to the requirement.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2005 code made it clearer that all outlets must be protected despite discussion in the code-making panel about excluding bedroom smoke detectors from the requirement.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] "Outlets" as defined in the NEC includes receptacles, light fixtures and smoke alarms, among other things.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Basically, any point where AC electricity is used to power something is an outlet.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] As of January 2008, only "combination type" AFCIs meet the NEC requirement.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2008 NEC requires the installation of combination-type AFCIs in all 15 and 20 ampere residential circuits with the exception of laundries, kitchens, bathrooms, garages, and unfinished basements, though many of these require GFCI protection.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2014 NEC adds kitchens and laundry rooms to the list of rooms requiring AFCI circuitry, as well as any devices (such as lighting) requiring protection.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] As of January 2023, there are a total of 6 means of protection covered as part of 210.12(A).
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A listed branch/feeder-type AFCI that is installed at the origin of the branch circuit working in combination with the listed outlet branch-circuit-type AFCI (OBC AFCI) installed at the first outlet box which must also be marked that it is the first outlet box of the branch circuit.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This option includes a listed "Supplemental Arc Protection Circuit Breaker" which does not exist.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] There is no standard for this device and so this is not an option that can be used.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This option does have a single manufacturer who has a solution on the market.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (b) Maximum length for a 14 AWG conductor is 50 ft and the maximum length for a 12 AWG conductor is 70ft.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (c) The first outlet box has to be marked as such.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (d) The circuit breaker and the OBC AFCI must be listed to meet the requirements of a system combination-type AFCI.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Options 5 and 6 are the same options as we've seen in this section in the past but just included as positive text instead of being an exception.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In the UK, the Wiring Regulations 18th edition (BS 7671:2018) is the first edition to make any mention of arc fault devices, and indicate they may be installed if the design has an unusually high risk of fire from arc faults.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The annexes relating to testing indicate that when AFDDs are installed, their correct operation must be verified before completion, but the method of testing is not described.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This is in contrast to RCDs where a number of trip times at different fault current levels must be verified.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Most power circuits in these countries fall under this clause as the common sockets are 10 A and 15 A rating.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The Australian standards are used in Argentina, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands and Papua New Guinea.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs are designed to protect against fires caused by electrical arc faults.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] While the sensitivity of the AFCIs helps in the detection of arc faults, these breakers can also indicate false positives by identifying normal circuit behaviors as arc faults.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] For instance, lightning strikes provide voltage and current profiles that resemble arc faults, and vacuum cleaners and some laser printers trip AFCIs.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This nuisance tripping reduces the overall effectiveness of AFCIs.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Research into advancements in this area is being pursued.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Sensitivities and mitigation have been known since 2013.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI circuit breakers include a standard inverse-time circuit breaker but provide no specific protection against "glowing" connections (also known as a high resistance connection), high line voltages, or low line voltages.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An AFCI does not detect high line voltage caused by an open neutral in a multiwire branch circuit.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A multiwire branch circuit uses both energized wires of a 120–240 V split phase service.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] If the neutral is broken along the return path to the circuit breaker panel, devices connected from a 120 V leg to the neutral may experience excess voltage, up to twice normal.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Low line voltage can cause electromechanical relays to repeatedly turn off and on, or "chatter".
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] If current is flowing through the load contacts, it causes arcing across the contacts as they open.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The arcing can oxidize, pit, and melt the contacts.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This process can increase the contact resistance, superheat the relay, and lead to fires.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Power fault circuit interrupters are designed to prevent fires from low voltage across loads.
[src:brownout-electricity/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs may interfere with the operation of some power line communication technologies.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] In an electric power system, **automatic generation control** (**AGC**) is a system for adjusting the power output of multiple generators at different power plants, in response to changes in the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Since a power grid requires that generation and load closely balance moment by moment, frequent adjustments to the output of generators are necessary.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] The balance can be judged by measuring the system frequency; if it is increasing, more power is being generated than used, which causes all the machines in the system to accelerate.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] If the system frequency is decreasing, more load is on the system than the instantaneous generation can provide, which causes all generators to slow down.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Before the use of automatic generation control, one generating unit in a system would be designated as the regulating unit and would be manually adjusted to control the balance between generation and load to maintain system frequency at the desired value.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] The remaining units would be controlled with speed droop to share the load in proportion to their ratings.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] With automatic systems, many units in a system can participate in regulation, reducing wear on a single unit's controls and improving overall system efficiency, stability, and economy.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Where the grid has tie interconnections to adjacent control areas, automatic generation control helps maintain the power interchanges over the tie lines at the scheduled levels.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Turbine generators in a power system have stored kinetic energy due to their large rotating masses.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] All the kinetic energy stored in a power system in such rotating masses is a part of the grid inertia.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] When system load increases, grid inertia is initially used to supply the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] This, however, leads to a decrease in the stored kinetic energy of the turbine generators.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Since the mechanical power of these turbines correlates with the delivered electrical power, the turbine generators have a decrease in angular velocity, which is directly proportional to a decrease in frequency in synchronous generators.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] The purpose of the turbine-governor control (TGC) is to maintain the desired system frequency by adjusting the mechanical power output of the turbine.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] For steam turbines, steam turbine governing adjusts the mechanical output of the turbine by increasing or decreasing the amount of steam entering the turbine via a throttle valve.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Load-frequency control (LFC) is employed to allow an area to first meet its own load demands, then to assist in returning the steady-state frequency of the system, Δf, to zero.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Load-frequency control operates with a response time of a few seconds to keep system frequency stable.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] The goal of economic dispatch is to minimize total operating costs in an area by determining how the real power output of each generating unit will meet a given load.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Generating units have different costs to produce a unit of electrical energy, and incur different costs for the losses in transmitting energy to the load.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] An economic dispatch algorithm will run every few minutes to select the combination of generating unit power setpoints that minimizes overall cost, subject to the constraints of transmission limitation or security of the system against failures.
[src:brownout-electricity/automatic-generation-control] Further constraints may be imposed by the water supply of hydroelectric generation, or by the availability of sun and wind power.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] The **availability factor** of a power plant is the duration it achieves production of electricity divided by the duration that it was planned to produce electricity.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] In the field of reliability engineering, *availability factor* is known as operational availability, $A_{o}$ .
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] The capacity factor of a plant includes numerous other factors which determine the durations the plant is planned to produce electricity.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] A solar photovoltaic plant is not planned to operate in the dark of a night, hence unplanned maintenance occurring whilst the sun is set does not impact the availability factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Periods of generation where only partial generation of planned capacity occurs may or may not be deducted from the availability factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] An example of partial generation is a power plant with four installed turbines planned to be concurrently operational, but one of those turbines subsequently requires unplanned maintenance.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Where deductions are made the metric is titled *equivalent availability factor* (EAF).
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] The availability of a power plant varies greatly depending on the type of fuel, the design of the plant and how the plant is operated.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Everything else being equal, plants that are run less frequently have higher availability factors because they require less maintenance and because more inspections and maintenance can be scheduled during idle time.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Most thermal power stations, such as coal, geothermal and nuclear power plants, have availability factors between 70% and 90%.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Newer plants tend to have significantly higher availability factors, but preventive maintenance is as important as improvements in design and technology.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Gas turbines have relatively high availability factors, ranging from 80% to 99%.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Gas turbines are commonly used for peaking power plants, co-generation plants and the first stage of combined cycle plants.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Originally the term availability factor was used only for power plants that depended on an active, controlled supply of fuel, typically fossil or later also nuclear.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] The emergence of renewable energy such as hydro, wind and solar power, which operate without an active, controlled supply of fuel and which come to a standstill when their natural supply of energy ceases, requires a more careful distinction between the availability factor and the capacity factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] By convention, such zero production periods are counted against the capacity factor but not against the availability factor, which thus remains defined as depending on an active, controlled supply of fuel, along with factors concerning reliability and maintenance.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] A wind turbine cannot operate in wind speeds above a certain limit, which counts against its availability factor.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] With this definition, modern wind turbines which require very little maintenance, have very high availability factors, up to about 98%.
[src:brownout-electricity/availability-factor] Photovoltaic power stations which have few or no moving parts and which can undergo planned inspections and maintenance during night have an availability factor approaching or equal to 100% when the sun is shining.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] Development and economization of consumer power generation equipment such as wind turbines and photovoltaic systems has led to an increase in the number of consumers that may produce more electrical power than they consume during peak generating conditions.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] If supported by the consumer's electric utility provider, the excess power generated may be fed back into the electrical grid.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] This process makes the typical consumer a temporary producer while the flow of electrical power remains reversed.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] When backfeeding is performed this way, electric utility providers will install a specially engineered electrical meter that is capable of net metering.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] A common source of unintentional backfeeding is an electrical generator (typically a portable generator) that is improperly connected to a building electrical system.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] A properly installed electrical generator incorporates the use of a transfer switch or generator interlock kit to ensure the incoming electrical service line is disconnected when the generator is providing power to the building.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] In the absence (or improper usage) of a transfer switch, unintentional backfeeding may occur when the power provided by the electrical generator is able to flow over the electrical service line.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] Because an electrical transformer is capable of operating in both directions, electrical power generated from equipment on the consumer's premises can backfeed through the transformer and energize the distribution line to which the transformer is connected.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] Backfeeding also exists in other instances where a location that is typically a generator becomes a consumer.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] This is commonly seen when an electrical generation plant is shut down or operating at such a reduced capacity that its parasitic load becomes greater than its generated power.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] The parasitic power load is the result of the usage of: pumps, facility lighting, HVAC equipment, and other control equipment that must remain active regardless of actual electrical power production.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] Electrical utilities often take steps to decrease their overall parasitic load to minimize this type of backfeeding and improve efficiency.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] For manufacturing cost and operational simplicity reasons, most circuit (overcurrent) protection and power quality control (voltage regulation) devices used by electric utility companies are designed with the assumption that power always flows in one direction.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] An interconnection agreement can be arranged for equipment designed to backfeed from the consumer's equipment to the electrical utility provider's distribution system.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] This type of interconnection can involve nontrivial engineering and usage of costly specialized equipment designed to keep distribution circuits and equipment properly protected.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] Such costs may be minimized by limiting distributed generation capacity to less than that which is consumed locally, and guaranteeing this condition by installing a reverse-power cutoff relay that opens if backfeeding occurs.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] Because it involves transfer of significant amounts of energy, backfeeding must be carefully controlled and monitored.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] Personnel working on equipment subject to backfeeding must be aware of all possible power sources, and follow systematic protocols to ensure that equipment is fully de-energized before commencing work, or use special equipment and techniques suitable for working on live equipment.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] When working on de-energized power conductors, lineworkers attach temporary protective grounding assemblies or "protective ground sets", which short all conductors to each other and to an earth ground.
[src:brownout-electricity/backfeeding] This ensures that no wires can become energized, whether by accidental switching or by unintentional backfeeding.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] A **brownout** is a drop in the magnitude of voltage in an electrical power system.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Unintentional brownouts can be caused by excessive electricity demand, severe weather events, or a malfunction or error affecting electrical grid control or monitoring systems.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Intentional brownouts are used for load reduction in an emergency, or to prevent a total grid power outage due to high demand.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] The term *brownout* comes from the dimming of incandescent lighting when voltage reduces.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] In some countries, the term *brownout* refers not to a drop in voltage but to an intentional or unintentional power outage (or blackout).
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Different types of electrical apparatus will react in different ways to a voltage reduction.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Some devices will be severely affected, while others may not be affected at all.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] The heat output of any resistive device, such as an electric space heater, toaster, oven, and incandescent bulbs is equal to the power consumption, which is directly proportional to the square of the applied voltage if the resistance stays constant.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Therefore, a significant reduction of heat output will occur with a relatively small reduction in voltage.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] An incandescent lamp will dim due to lower heat creation in the filament, as well as lower conversion of heat to light.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Generally speaking, no damage will occur but functionality will be impaired.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Commutated electric motors, such as universal motors, will run at reduced speed or reduced torque.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Depending on the motor design, no harm may occur.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] However, under load, the motor may draw more current due to the reduced back-EMF developed at the lower armature speed.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Unless the motor has ample cooling capacity, it may eventually overheat and burn out.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] An induction motor will draw more current to compensate for the decreased voltage, which may lead to overheating and burnout.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] If a substantial part of a grid's load is electric motors, reducing voltage may not actually reduce load and can result in damage to customers' equipment.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] An unregulated DC supply will produce a lower output voltage.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] The output voltage ripple will decrease in line with the usually reduced load current.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] In a cathode-ray tube television, the reduced output voltage will make the screen image smaller, dimmer and fuzzier.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] A switched-mode power supply will be affected if the brownout voltage is lower than the minimum input voltage of the power supply.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] As the input voltage falls, the current draw will increase to maintain the same output voltage and current, until such a point that the power supply malfunctions or its under-voltage protection kicks in and disables the output.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Brownouts can cause unexpected behavior in systems with digital control circuits.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] Reduced voltages can bring control signals below the threshold at which logic circuits can reliably detect which state is being represented.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] As the voltage returns to normal levels the logic can latch at an incorrect state; to the extent that even "can't happen" states become possible.
[src:brownout-electricity/brownout-electricity] The seriousness of this effect and whether steps need to be taken by the designer to prevent it depends on the nature of the equipment being controlled; for instance, a brownout may cause a motor to begin running backwards.
